'''Elliot Junior Anderson''' (born 6 November 2002) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|NottingF}} club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].

==Early life==
Anderson hails from [[Whitley Bay]], [[Tyne and Wear]]. He was a pupil at [[Valley Gardens Middle School]] and [[Whitley Bay High School]].

His maternal grandfather, [[Geoff Allen (footballer)|Geoff Allen]], played as an outside-left for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] from 1964 to 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newcastleunited.com/en/news/anderson-wants-to-keep-following-in-grandfathers-footsteps-after-signing-new-contract|title=Anderson wants to keep following in grandfather's footsteps after signing new contract|publisher=Newcastle United F.C.|first=Dan|last=King|date=6 November 2020|accessdate=21 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/introducing-elliot-anderson/|title=Introducing Elliot Anderson|publisher=Newcastle United F.C.|first=Luke|last=Vinton|date=27 November 2020|accessdate=21 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/elliot-anderson-newcastle-geoff-allen-19622397|title='I was so proud' – Geoff Allen's dream lives on with grandson Elliot Anderson|website=ChronicleLive|first=John|last=Gibson|date=14 January 2021|accessdate=21 March 2021}}</ref> He has an elder brother, Wil Anderson, who appeared on the 11th season of [[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Duke |first=Simon |date=14 June 2024 |title=Wil Anderson arrives on Love Island as ITV star has Premier League link |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/tv/who-wil-anderson-love-island-29354885 |access-date=29 August 2025 |website=Chronicle Live |language=en}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Newcastle United===
Anderson first joined [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] at the age of eight having previously been at [[Wallsend Boys Club]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/introducing-elliot-anderson/|title=Introducing Elliot Anderson|website=www.nufc.co.uk|date=27 November 2020|accessdate=20 February 2022}}</ref> and signed his first professional contract with the club in November 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/elliot-anderson-signs-first-professional-contract-with-newcastle-united/|title=Elliot Anderson signs first professional contract with Newcastle United|website=www.nufc.co.uk|date=8 November 2019|accessdate=20 February 2022}}</ref> signing another long-term deal a year later on his eighteenth birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/teenage-midfielder-elliot-anderson-signs-new-long-term-deal/|title=Teenage midfielder Elliot Anderson signs new long-term deal|website=www.nufc.co.uk|date=6 November 2020|accessdate=20 February 2022}}</ref> On 9 January 2021, Anderson made his first-team debut in a 2–0 defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the [[2020–21 FA Cup#Third round proper|third round]] of the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55574495|title=Arsenal 2–0 Newcastle United|publisher=BBC Sport|date=9 January 2021|accessdate=21 March 2021}}</ref> On 18 January, Anderson made his [[Premier League]] debut against the same opposition in a 3–0 defeat, as an 87th-minute [[substitute (association football)|substitute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55613917|title=Arsenal 3–0 Newcastle United|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Michael|last=Emons|date=18 January 2021|accessdate=21 March 2021}}</ref>

====Bristol Rovers (loan)====
On 31 January 2022, Anderson joined [[EFL League Two|League Two]] side [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] on [[loan (sports)|loan]] until the end of the [[2021–22 Bristol Rovers F.C. season|2021–22 season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bristolrovers.co.uk/news/2022/january/elliot-anderson-signs-for-rovers/|publisher=Bristol Rovers F.C.|title=Elliot Anderson Signs For Rovers!|date=31 January 2022|access-date=31 January 2022}}</ref> He made his debut on 5 February, impressing off of the bench in a 1–1 draw at [[Sutton United F.C.|Sutton United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60178837|title=Sutton United 1–1 Bristol Rovers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=5 February 2022|accessdate=6 February 2022}}</ref> Anderson opened his account for the club, scoring the first league goal of his career, with the second in a 4–0 away win at [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] before assisting namesake [[Harry Anderson (English footballer)|Harry Anderson]] for the third four minutes later<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60357384|title=Stevenage 0–4 Bristol Rovers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 February 2022|accessdate=19 February 2022}}</ref> in a performance that was rated 9/10 by local media outlet ''[[Bristol Post|Bristol Live]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/bristol-rovers-player-ratings-vs-6688954|title=Bristol Rovers player ratings vs Stevenage: Elliot Anderson and Sam Finley rampant|publisher=Bristol Post|last1=Frost|first1=Sam|date=19 February 2022|accessdate=20 February 2022}}</ref> Following a 1–0 victory over [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] in which Anderson scored the only goal of the game, his third goal for the club and scoring for a second consecutive match, manager and former Newcastle midfielder [[Joey Barton]] compared Anderson's style of play to that of [[Diego Maradona]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/elliot-anderson-barton-maradona-newcastle-23401828|title=Joey Barton compares Newcastle youngster Elliot Anderson to Diego Maradona after Bristol Rovers win|first=Charlie|last=Bennett|website=Chronicle Live|date=16 March 2022|access-date=16 March 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/bristol-rovers-player-ratings-vs-6808873|title=Bristol Rovers player ratings vs Colchester: Elliot Anderson's star shines brightest|publisher=Bristol Post|last1=Frost|first1=Sam|date=15 March 2022|accessdate=16 March 2022}}</ref> Anderson was awarded the League Two Goal of the Month award for March 2022 for his impressive solo run and finish against [[Harrogate Town A.F.C.|Harrogate Town]], receiving 50% of the public vote.<ref name="Mar22 GOTM">{{cite news |url=https://www.bristolrovers.co.uk/news/2022/april/elliot-goal-of-the-month/|title=Elliot Anderson Wins Goal of the Month Award For March!|website=Bristol Rovers F.C.|date=15 April 2022|access-date=15 April 2022}}</ref> On 7 May 2022, Anderson was awarded the [[EFL Young Player of the Month]] Award for April 2022 after three goals and two assists in six matches left Rovers close to an automatic promotion spot,<ref name="Apr22 YPOTM">{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2022/may/elliot-anderson-named-efl-young-player-of-the-month--for-april/|title=Elliot Anderson Named EFL Young Player of The Month for April|website=www.efl.com|date=7 May 2022|accessdate=8 May 2022}}</ref> later winning the [[EFL League Two Player of the Month]] Award too.<ref name="Apr22 POTM">{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2022/may/sky-bet-efl-manager-and-player-of-the-month-april-winners/|title=Sky Bet EFL Manager and Player of the Month April winners!|website=www.efl.com|date=13 May 2022|accessdate=13 May 2022}}</ref> That same day, the final league match of the season, Anderson scored Rovers' final goal in the 85th minute of a 7–0 thrashing of [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], this goal moving Rovers above [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] on a goals scored basis into the final automatic promotion spot, the club returning to League One at the first time of asking.<ref name="21/22 Promotion"> {{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61281127|title=Bristol Rovers go up after extraordinary 7–0 win|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 May 2022|accessdate=8 May 2022}}</ref>

====Return to Newcastle and breakthrough====
On 21 September 2022, Anderson's breakthrough into the first-team was rewarded with a new long-term contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/anderson-signs-new-long-term-deal-with-magpies/|title=Anderson signs new long-term deal with Magpies|website=www.nufc.co.uk|date=21 September 2022|accessdate=21 September 2022}}</ref> On 26 February 2023, he came off the bench in the 91st minute of the [[2023 EFL Cup final]] defeat to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref name="eflcup">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64693810|title=Manchester United 2–0 Newcastle United: Erik ten Hag's side win Carabao Cup for first trophy since 2017|first=Phil|last=McNulty|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 February 2023|access-date=26 February 2023}}</ref> He was controversially denied a first Newcastle goal on 17 March 2023 at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] when his back-post [[header (association football)|header]] was ruled out by [[Video assistant referee|VAR]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64911104|title=Nottingham Forest 1–2 Newcastle United: Alexander Isak scores dramatic late winner over Forest|first=Emma|last=Sanders|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 March 2023|access-date=19 March 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/football/12836760/gary-neville-8216bemused8217-that-elliot-anderson8217s-goal-was-disallowed|title=Gary Neville 'bemused' that Elliot Anderson's goal was disallowed|website=www.skysports.com|date=17 March 2023|accessdate=19 March 2023}}</ref> A decision described as "bizarre",<ref name=disallowedGoal2023/> while former referee [[Dermot Gallagher]] clarified with evidence that no [[offside (association football)|offside]] law had been broken.<ref name=disallowedGoal2023>{{Cite tweet |user=SkySportsPL |number=1637783643417346049 |title="I don't get why it's not been given as a goal"}}</ref>

Anderson's development continued throughout the season, resulting in an increased presence in pre-season for the 2023–24 campaign, where he garnered much praise.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Edwards |first=Luke |date=2 August 2023 |title=Young midfielder hailed as 'new Gazza' and Geordie wonderkid, 17, lighting up Newcastle's pre-season |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/08/02/newcastle-preseason-elliot-anderson-lewis-miley-shine/ |access-date=1 April 2024 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> In the season, Anderson's development continued with an increased first team presence, starting 4 matches, and having substitute appearances in the other 5 Premier League matches, before he was sidelined for 4 months with a lower back injury. Anderson returned to the team on 27 February 2024, scoring in the [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in the [[2023–24 FA Cup|FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68404007|title=Blackburn 1–1 Newcastle (3–4 on penalties): Premier League side move into FA Cup quarter-finals|first=Michael|last=Emons|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 February 2024|access-date=1 April 2024}}</ref>

=== Nottingham Forest ===
On 1 July 2024, Anderson joined [[Premier League]] side [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] for a reported fee of £35 million,<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 July 2024 |title=Newcastle transfers: Elliot Anderson completes £35m move to Nottingham Forest and Yankuba Minteh joins Brighton for £30m |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12040/13161291/newcastle-transfers-elliot-anderson-completes-35m-move-to-nottingham-forest-and-yankuba-minteh-joins-brighton-for-30m |access-date=1 July 2024 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> signing a five-year contract with the club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 July 2024 |title=Forest complete signing of Elliot Anderson |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2024/june/30/forest-complete-signing-of-elliot-anderson/ |access-date=1 July 2024 |website=Nottingham Forest Football Club}}</ref> A later article in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' newspaper had the transfer fee as "around £15 million".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2024/07/13/nottingham-forest-launch-13m-bid-for-fiorentina-centre-back/|url-access=subscription|title=Nottingham Forest launch £13m bid for Fiorentina centre-back Nikola Milenković|first=John|last=Percy|website=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 July 2024|accessdate=15 July 2024}}</ref> Following an impressive start to the season, he was named as the club's player of the month for August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2024/september/09/anderson-voted-august-player-of-the-month/|title=Anderson voted August Player of the Month|website=www.nottinghamforest.co.uk|date=9 September 2024|accessdate=25 January 2025}}</ref> On 19 January 2025, he scored his first Premier League goal in a 3–2 victory over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/crr09rxy7ngt|title=Nottingham Forest 3–2 Southampton: Forest move level on points with second-place Arsenal|first=Matthew|last=Henry|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 January 2025|access-date=25 January 2025}}</ref> In the [[2025–26 Premier League|2025–26 season]], he finished the campaign as the league leader in touches (3,300), duels won (297), fouls won (80), and possessions won (306).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cgmppp4x34eo |title=Anderson makes Opta's team of the season |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==

=== Youth career ===
Born in England, Anderson is of English and Scottish descent with a grandmother on his father's side born in Glasgow and later residing in Whitley Bay. He was a youth international for Scotland at U16, U17 and U18 level.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/how-toon-teen-elliot-anderson-17267757|title=How Toon teen Elliot Anderson went from Level 7 and idolising Yohan Cabaye to a deal with NUFC|first=Lee|last=Ryder|website=Chronicle Live|date=17 November 2019|access-date=9 January 2021}}</ref> He switched his allegiance to England in March 2021, making his debut in an unofficial friendly for England under-19s against [[Arsenal F.C. Under-21s and Academy|Arsenal U23]]s on 27 March 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/elliot-anderson-england-debut-hand-20271613|title=England U19s hand Elliot Anderson a Three Lions debut at St George's Park|first=Lee|last=Ryder|website=Chronicle Live|date=27 March 2021|access-date=28 March 2021}}</ref> Anderson was selected in the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21]] squad in November 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/10-performance-school-players-named-in-scotland-under-21-squad/?rid=13925 |title=10 Performance School players named in Scotland Under-21 squad |website=scottishfa.co.uk |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=28 October 2021 |access-date=28 October 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59080078 |title=Newcastle United's Elliot Anderson called into Scotland U21 squad after England appearance |website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 October 2021 |access-date=28 October 2021}}</ref> Anderson received a second call-up for the Scotland U21 squad in March 2022,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/scotland-under-21-squad-named-for-double-header-against-turkey-and-kazakhstan/?rid=14258|title=Scotland Under-21 squad named for double-header against Turkey and Kazakhstan|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk|date=9 March 2022|accessdate=10 March 2022}}</ref> instead opting to remain with his loan club Bristol Rovers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/bristol-rovers-newcastle-united-anderson-6856621|title=Triple boost for Bristol Rovers with Newcastle United starlet available despite Scotland call-up|publisher=Bristol Post|last1=Frost|first1=Sam|date=24 March 2022|accessdate=13 April 2022}}</ref> Anderson made his Scotland under-21 debut on 5 June as they held group leaders [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium]] to a 0–0 draw.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61698438|title=Belgium U21 0–0 Scotland U21|first=Clive|last=Lindsay|publisher=BBC Sport|date=5 June 2022|access-date=5 June 2022}}</ref> He withdrew from a later Scotland under-21 squad, as he wanted to keep other representative options open.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/elliot-anderson-england-scotland-newcastle-26470496 |title=Scotland 'door still open' for Newcastle United star Elliot Anderson amid England tug-of-war |newspaper=Newcastle Chronicle |first=George |last=Bennett |date=14 March 2023 |accessdate=28 August 2023}}</ref>

In August 2023, Anderson received his first call-up to the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]] by head coach [[Steve Clarke]], for a [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] match against [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] and a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] against [[England national football team|England]],<ref>{{cite web |date=28 August 2023 |title=Steve Clarke confirms squad for Cyprus and England matches |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/steve-clarke-confirms-squad-for-cyprus-and-england-matches/?rid=14258 |access-date=28 August 2023 |website= |publisher=[[Scottish FA]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=28 August 2023 |title=Scotland call up Elliot Anderson for matches with Cyprus and England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66638163 |access-date=28 August 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> but pulled out due to injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/newcastle-starlet-elliot-anderson-pulls-out-of-scotland-squad-after-knock-in-training-4281875|title=Newcastle starlet Elliot Anderson pulls out of Scotland squad after knock in training|first=Alan|last=Pattullo|website=The Scotsman|date=5 September 2023|access-date=5 September 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Pirie |first=Mark |date=13 September 2023 |title=Elliot Anderson to snub Scotland as Newcastle star opts to chase England call|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/elliot-anderson-snub-scotland-after-30935545 |access-date=14 September 2023 |website=Daily Record |language=en}}</ref>

On 30 August 2024, Anderson received a first call up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] squad for [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|UEFA Euro U21 qualifying]] fixtures against [[Northern Ireland national under-21 football team|Northern Ireland]] and [[Austria national under-21 football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2024/Aug/30/england-mens-under-21s-squad-named-for-northern-ireland-austria-20243008|title=England MU21s squad named for Northern Ireland and Austria|first=Nicholas|last=Veevers|website=EnglandFootball.com|date=30 August 2024|access-date=30 August 2024}}</ref> Elliot made a further two appearances on the 11 and 15 October 2024. Against [[Ukraine national under-21 football team|Ukraine]] and [[Azerbaijan national under-21 football team|Azerbaijan]], the latter of which he scored his first goal, in a 7–0 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c4g549knvq8t|title=England U21 7–0 Azerbaijan U21|first=Michael|last=Emons|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 October 2024|access-date=2 July 2025}}</ref>

Anderson was included in the [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship squads#England|England squad]] for the [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c0k321x3e7ko|title=England bid to defend Under-21 crown – plus who else could star|first=Michael|last=Emons|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 June 2025|access-date=2 July 2025}}</ref> He scored the last goal of their quarter-final victory over [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/jun/21/spain-england-european-under-21-championship-match-report|title=Elliot Anderson finishes off Spain as England Under-21s reach Euros' last four|first=Ed|last=Aarons|website=The Guardian|date=21 June 2025|access-date=2 July 2025}}</ref> Anderson started in the [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship final|final]] as England defeated [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] after extra time to lift the trophy.<ref name="U21">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cz6g18dz2dpt|title=England U-21 3 Germany U-21 2|first=Nick|last=Mashiter|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 June 2025|access-date=28 June 2025}}</ref> His performances during the competition resulted in him being chosen by the UEFA Technical Observer panel for their team of the tournament.<ref name="tott">{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/news/029b-1e218d6c7f6f-b542bb91eb18-1000--2025-under-21-euro-team-of-the-tournament/|title=2025 Under-21 EURO Team of the Tournament|newspaper=UEFA|date=1 July 2025|access-date=2 July 2025}}</ref>

Anderson received a first senior England call-up by [[England national football team manager|England manager]] [[Thomas Tuchel]] on 29 August 2025, for [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group K|2026 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]] and [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=England drop Alexander-Arnold, Spence & Anderson called up|first=Sami|last=Mokbel|date=29 August 2025|accessdate=29 August 2025|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cz605jj5e87o}}</ref> He made his England debut on 6 September in a 2–0 win against Andorra.<ref>{{cite news|title=England 2–0 Andorra: England maintain 100% record with uninspiring win over Andorra|first=Phil|last=McNulty|date=6 September 2025|accessdate=6 September 2025|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cly7yzvx6kzt}}</ref>

